{"id":"59","paper":{"title":{"text":"Effects of domain-specific SVM kernel design for speech recognition application "},"authors":[{"name":"Cvetkovic, Zoran"},{"name":"Yousafzai, Jibran"},{"name":"Sollich, Peter"}],"abstr":{"text":"We consider the effects of incorporating prior knowledge of features which correlate with phoneme identity as well perceptual invariances to design SVM kernels for phoneme classification in high-dimensional spaces of acoustic waveforms of speech. To this end we explore products and linear combinations of  polynomial and radial basis function kernels to design composite kernels which are invariant to waveform sign and time shift, and capture the dynamics of energy evolution in the time-frequency plane.  Experiments show marked improvements in phoneme classification as a result of this custom kernel design. This demonstrates that even in high-dimensional feature spaces, careful kernel design based on prior knowledge of the problem domain can have significant payback."},"body":{"text":"Spherical coverings. Let B n r (x) be the ball (solid sphere) centered at some point x = (x 1 , . . . , x n ) of an n-dimensional Euclidean space R n :\nWe also use a simpler notation B n r if a ball is centered at the origin x = 0. For any subset A ⊂ R n , we say that a subset Cov(A, ε) ⊆ R n forms an ε-covering (an ε-net) of A if A is contained in the union of the balls of radius ε centered at points x ∈ Cov(A, ε) :\nBy changing the scale in R n , we can always consider the rescaled set A/ε and the new covering Cov(A/ε, 1) with unit balls B n 1 (x). Without loss of generality, below we consider these (unit) coverings. One of the classical problems is to obtain tight bounds on the covering size |Cov(B n r , 1)| for any ball B n r of radius r and dimension n.\nThen the unit balls B n+1 1 (x) cover this sphere with spherical caps\nIn this notation, a cap C n r (ρ, y) has some center y ∈ S n r , half- chord ρ ≤ 1, and the corresponding half-angle α = arcsin ρ/r. The maximum half-chord ρ = 1 is obtained if the center x of the ball B n+1 1 (x) has Euclidean weight\nTo obtain a minimal covering, we shall consider spherical caps C n r (1, y) assuming that all the balls B n+1 1 (x) satisfy (1). Throughout the paper, all caps will be considered in\nS n r ; therefore we use a shorter notation C(ρ, y) instead of C n r (ρ, y). Notation C(ρ) will also be used when a speciﬁc center y is of no importance.\nSpherical coverings often arise in multidimensional (vec- tor) quantizers [5]. In particular, consider n-dimensional data points z ∈ R n+1 that have the same energy r 2 and are uniformly distributed in the sphere S n r . A typical quantizer provides a covering {x} of the sphere S n r which limits the mean (squared) rounding error (x − z) 2 . Zador\u2019s theorem [5] shows that this error can be reduced per dimension by using quantization in higher dimensions n. In this case, given the maximum rounding error ε caused by a quantizer, we wish to ﬁnd the thinnest ε-covering Cov(S n r ) of the sphere S n r .\nPreliminaries. Given a set A of volume |A| , the two important quantities are the minimal covering size |Cov(A, 1)| and the covering density\nMinimal coverings have been long studied for both the sphere S n r and the ball B n r . In particular, we mention the following results. The Coxeter-Few-Rogers \u201csimplex\u201d bound shows that for any sphere S n r of radius r ≥ 1 + 1 n 1/2 ,\nHere and below c i denote some universal constants. Various upper bounds on the minimum covering density are obtained for B n r and S n r in the renowned papers [1] and [2]. In particular, a sufﬁciently large ball B n r can be covered with the density\nFor smaller radii r, recent advances are obtained in [3] and [4]. In particular, it is proven in [3] (see Corollary 1.2 and Remark 5.1) that for any radius r,\nTheorem 1: For any β > 1 2 , a sphere S n r of any radius r and growing dimension n → ∞ can be covered with spherical caps C(1, y) of half-chord 1 with density\nNotation. Below we consider a sphere S n r for growing dimension n → ∞ and any given radius r > 1. Consider any cap C(ρ) of half-chord ρ ≤ 1 and half-angle α = arcsin ρ r . Let\ndenote the fraction of the surface of the sphere S n r covered by a cap C (ρ) . For any ρ < 1, we extensively use two inequalities (see [3]):\nGiven any d ∈ (0, r), we say that the two caps, C(ρ 1 , y) and C(ρ 2 , z) are d-close if (vectors) y and z have angle\nFinally, we use a shorter notation Cov(ρ) for any covering of the sphere S n r with spherical caps of half-chord ρ.\nTo design a covering Cov(1), we shall also use another covering\nwith smaller caps C(ε, u). In general, Cov(ε) with density δ has size\nHere we allow to employ any redundant covering, whose density δ can be much greater than n ln n. Then we try to directly cover all the centers u ∈ Cov (ε) by the randomly chosen caps C(ρ, y). We use positive parameter γ and stop after performing\ntrials (here we assume that N is an integer). We consider all uncovered centers u ∈ Cov (ε) and form the extended set\nObviously, this set forms a covering Cov (1) of the sphere S n r with the bigger caps C(1, y).\nThen the sphere S n r has a covering Cov (1) of size ¯ Y ≤ n ln n\nvalid for any ε ∈ (0, 1). Also, according to (6), Ω 1 /Ω ε ≤ ε −n .\nNow we use (10) to ﬁnd the expected number E |{u }| of uncovered centers\nwhere we used a substitution from (11) in the last inequality. Then we estimate N. From (6) and (7), we deduce that\nHere the second inequality can be numerically veriﬁed for any 3 ≤ n ≤ 7, while for n ≥ 8 it follows from (14). Therefore\nThen our covering ¯ Y of size N +E |{u }| gives estimates (12) and (13).\nDiscussion. Assume that we use a covering Cov (ε) of polynomial density δ = n c . Then it is readily veriﬁed that for large n, bound (11) gives an estimate\nwhich is similar to the estimate of [3] and the above bound (2). Note, however, that (16) is valid even if we use an exponential density δ = e cn in