e S n r : Cov(µ) : S n r ⊆\nWe assume that both coverings have density δ ≤ n 2 . Then Cov(ε) has size (9) and\npoints y ∈ S n r . Consider N spherical caps C(ρ, y). Then we examine the centers u of the covering Cov (ε) as follows.\nLet C(µ, ˇ z) be any cap of the covering Cov (µ) that contains at least one center u ∈ Cov (ε) yet uncovered by the bigger caps C(ρ, y). We consider the entire set {ˇ z} of such centers.\nNote that any point on the sphere S n r falls within distance ε from the union of the caps C(ρ, y) with centers y ∈ ¯ Y . Therefore, the extended caps C(1, y) form a covering\n¯ Y ≤ Ω −1 d · γn ln n (1 + o(1)) . \t (20) We begin with the following important lemma.\nLemma 4: Consider two d-close caps, C(µ, Z) and C(ρ, Y) on a sphere S n r ,\nwhere d is deﬁned in (17). Then the bigger cap C(ρ, Y) covers the smaller cap C(µ, Z), with an exception of its fraction\nSketch of the proof. In Fig. 1, we represent the two caps C(µ, Z) and C(ρ, Y), with centers Z and Y. These two caps have bases P QRS and P M RT, which form the balls B n µ (A) and B n ρ (B). The bigger cap C(ρ, Y) covers the base B n µ (A) of the smaller cap, with an exception of the part P QR. Note that the boundary of the base B n µ (A) is the sphere S n−1 µ (A). In turn, the boundary of the uncovered base P QR forms a cap on S n−1 µ (A) with center Q and half-angle α = P AQ. We ﬁrst estimate this half-angle α.\nLet d(H, G) denote the distance between any two points H and G. Also, let σ(H) be the distance from a point H to the line OBY that connects the origin O of the sphere S n r to the base center B and then to the cap center Y. Then\nwhere we use (21) for the second inequality. On the other hand,\nFinally, note that by deﬁnition of the center B, d(B, N) = σ(N) and\nTherefore, we consider the right triangle ANP and deduce that\nNow we can calculate the fraction Ω that the cap P QR occupies on the sphere S n−1 µ (A). This fraction Ω is deﬁned in (5) by its angle α, which gives\nFinally, it can be easily proven that the uncovered fraction θ of the entire cap C(µ, Z) is upper-bounded by the uncovered fraction Ω of its base.\nRemark. The choice of d in (21) is critical for Lemma 4. In fact, about half the cap C(µ, Z) becomes uncovered if the two caps used in Lemma 4 are (d + ε)-close. If this distance is further increased to ρ, then C(µ, Z) becomes almost uncovered.\nOur next goal is to prove that most centers z have sufﬁ- ciently many d-close caps C(ρ, y) after N trials. Namely, let N caps C(ρ, y) be randomly chosen. We separate all spherical caps C(µ, z) into two subsets as follows. We say that a cap C(µ, z) is bad and denote it C (µ, z) if it has only\nor less d-close caps C(ρ, y). Let {C (µ, z)} be the subset of all bad caps, whereas {C (µ, z)} includes the remaining (good) caps. We ﬁrst prove that the mean number N of bad caps is negligible even to the number of random trials N.\nLemma 5: For n → ∞, any cap C(µ, z) is bad with a probability\nProof. Given any center z, a randomly chosen cap C(ρ, y) is d-close to z with the probability p = Ω d . Thus, for N of (18), the expected number of d-close caps C(ρ, y) is\nThen for n → ∞, the probability P that l = o(n) or less caps are d-close is\nIn our last equality, we again use the fact that l = n 3/2−β is sublinear in n ( in fact, the above function o(1) has the order of n 1/2−β ). Thus, given the covering size |Cov(µ)| = δ/Ω µ , we calculate the expected number of bad caps,\nd µ\nwhich is an exponentially small fraction o (N ) of N for any γ > β.\nThe second important fact is that most remaining caps C (µ, z) are covered almost entirely. Namely, let N be the total number of centers u ∈ Cov (ε) left uncovered in all the caps C (µ, z).\nLemma 6: For n → ∞, the number of uncovered centers u ∈ Cov (ε) has expectation\nProof. There exist at most |Cov(ε)| centers u within all caps C (µ, z). Any cap C (µ, z) is covered at least l times. Each time, a random fraction θ of its surface is left uncovered. Therefore any point u ∈ C (µ, z) is left uncovered with probability θ l , according to Lemma 4. Thus,\nHere in the last inequality we use the fact that n ln n = o(n β+ 1/2 ) for any β > 1/2 and sufﬁciently large n, which gives a vanishing fraction (4).\nProof of Claim 3 and Theorem 1. According to Lemmas 5 and 6, there exists a set of N caps C(ρ, y) that leaves only N = o (N ) bad caps C (µ, z ) and N = o (N ) uncovered centers u ∈ Cov (ε). Let C (µ, z ) be any cap within the set C with an uncovered center u . Now we take the set of additional centers\nand surround all of them with the caps C(ρ, ˇ z). The total number of these new caps is o(N ), which gives Claim 3.\nhas size ¯ N = N +o(N ). By extending all these caps to radius 1, we obtain a 1-covering of density\nFinally, we prove that Ω d ∼ Ω 1 for sufﬁciently large n. Similarly to the proof of Lemma 2, we see that for n → ∞\nSince both parameters β and γ can be chosen arbitrarily close to 1/2, this proves (4) and completes the proof of Theorem 1.\nRemark. The latter two lemmas also explain our choice of parameter l. First, for any γ > β, it gives only an exponentially small fraction o (N ) of bad caps in Lemma 5. On the other hand, it gives a vanishing fraction o (N ) of uncovered centers in (24) for any β > 1/2.\nThe following Theorem 7 can be proven in a similar way, by combining the technique of Theorem 1 with multilayered design described in [2] and [4].\nTheorem 7: For any β > 1 2 , a ball B n r of growing radius r → ∞ and dimension n → ∞ can be covered with unit balls B n 1 (x) with density\nCorollary 8: Euclidean spaces R n of growing dimension n → ∞ can be covered with unit balls B n 1 (x) with density"},"refs":[{"authors":[{"name":"A. Rogers"}],"title":{"text":"A note on coverings"}},{"authors":[{"name":"A. Rogers"}],"title":{"text":"Covering a sphere with spheres"}},{"authors":[{"name":"K. B¨or¨oczky"},{"name":"G. Wintsche"}],"title":{"text":"Covering the sphere with equal spherical balls"}},{"authors":[{"name":"J.